## Selamat Datang / Welcome to the Indonesian Portal

This is where the vastness of Indonesia is laid bare. A country of islands, oceans, and an astonishing diversity of life and culture.

The [flag of Indonesia](/Flag_of_Indonesia) – a simple red and white, yet it carries the weight of a nation. And there’s a map, of course. Because you’ll need one.

[Indonesia](/Indonesia), officially the Republic of Indonesia, is a nation sprawled across [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia) and [Oceania](/Oceania), a strategic nexus between the [Indian](/Indian_Ocean) and [Pacific](/Pacific_Ocean) oceans. Forget neat borders; this is a realm of over [17,000 islands](/List_of_islands_of_Indonesia). Think Sumatra, Java, Sulawesi, and the western fringes of Borneo and New Guinea. It’s the world's largest [archipelagic state](/Archipelagic_state), a colossal entity that ranks as the [14th-largest country by area](/List_of_countries_and_dependencies_by_area), covering an expanse of 1,904,569 square kilometers (735,358 square miles). And people? It has more than 280 million souls, making it the [fourth-most-populous country](/List_of_countries_and_dependencies_by_population) globally, and notably, the most populous [Muslim-majority country](/Islam_by_country). Java, its most populous island, acts as the demographic heart, housing over half the nation's inhabitants.

Indonesia operates under a [presidential republic](/Presidential_system), its governance steered by an elected [legislature](/People%27s_Consultative_Assembly). Administratively, it’s divided into [38 provinces](/Provinces_of_Indonesia), with nine of these enjoying [special autonomous status](/Autonomous_administrative_division). [Jakarta](/Jakarta), the sprawling capital, is not just a city; it’s the world's [second-most-populous urban area](/List_of_largest_cities). Indonesia’s land borders are shared with [Papua New Guinea](/Papua_New_Guinea), [Timor-Leste](/Timor-Leste), and [East Malaysia](/East_Malaysia). Its maritime reach extends to [Singapore](/Singapore), [Peninsular Malaysia](/Peninsular_Malaysia), [Vietnam](/Vietnam), [Thailand](/Thailand), the [Philippines](/Philippines), [Australia](/Australia), [Palau](/Palau), and [India](/India). Despite its dense population centers, Indonesia retains vast swathes of untouched wilderness, a sanctuary for some of the [world's highest levels of biodiversity](/Megadiverse_countries).

The fabric of Indonesian society is woven from hundreds of [ethnic](/Ethnic_groups_in_Indonesia) and [linguistic](/Languages_of_Indonesia) groups, with the [Javanese](/Javanese_people) forming the largest thread. The national identity, however, is bound by the motto [Bhinneka Tunggal Ika](/Bhinneka_Tunggal_Ika) – "Unity in Diversity." This identity is shaped by a shared [national language](/Indonesian_language), a mosaic of cultural and religious expressions, and a history steeped in [colonialism](/Colonialism) and the fierce struggle against it. As a [newly industrialised country](/Newly_industrialised_country), Indonesia's [economy](/Economy_of_Indonesia) is a significant force, ranking as the world's [17th-largest by nominal GDP](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)) and the [7th-largest by PPP](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)). It stands as the world's third-largest democracy and wields considerable influence as a [middle power](/Middle_power) on the global stage. Indonesia is an active participant in numerous multilateral organizations, including the [United Nations](/United_Nations), [World Trade Organization](/World_Trade_Organization), the [G20](/G20), [MIKTA](/MIKTA), and [BRICS](/BRICS). It was also a founding member of the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Non-Aligned_Movement), the [Association of Southeast Asian Nations](/ASEAN), the [East Asia Summit](/East_Asia_Summit), [APEC](/Asia-Pacific_Economic_Cooperation), and the [Organisation of Islamic Cooperation](/Organisation_of_Islamic_Cooperation). ( [Full article...](/Indonesia) )

